article.description:
Antawn Jamison scored 27 points and
grabbed 15 rebounds in the Wizards' 98-85 victory over the Atlanta
Hawks on Saturday night.
article.headline: Jamison's double-double leads Wizards past Hawks
article.linkText: Jamison's double-double leads Wizards past Hawks
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Antawn Jamison had three stitches in his lip, his 23rd double-double, and the admiration of teammate Caron Butler. "He's my idol," Butler said after Jamison scored 27 points and grabbed 15 rebounds in the Wizards' 98-85 victory over the Atlanta Hawks on Saturday night. "He carries himself well on and off the court, plus he's got on Louis Vuitton shoes. I like that." All kidding aside, Jamison has shouldered much of Washington's scoring and rebounding load as the Wizards have won nine of their past 13 games. "He's been the spark plug, hitting big shots when we need them," Butler said of Jamison, who is two rebounds shy of 4,000 in his eighth NBA season. "Like I told him, I hope that he makes the All-Star team. That would be big for him and for this organization. But if not, he's an All-Star in our minds. He's hitting the glass hard and making other guys better." Gilbert Arenas added 22 points as the Wizards snapped Atlanta's three-game winning streak. The Hawks had won three in a row for the first time since April 9-12, 2004. The Wizards, who have won eight straight against the Hawks, won for the third time in four games and got within a victory of the .500 mark for the first time since Dec. 6. "It's going to happen one of these days," Arenas said of the elusive mark Jamison has declared as the Wizards' goal before the All-Star break. "That's how I look at it. Every time we get close, something else happens. We just have to keep fighting." Butler had 18 points and seven rebounds for Washington, which is in the midst of a stretch of playing seven of eight games at home. The Wizards opened a season-high, five-game homestand against the Hawks. Joe Johnson led Atlanta with 16 points. Tyronn Lue added 14 points and Zaza Pachulia 13. "We had guys come off the bench who gave us some great productive minutes, and they got us in position to win," Johnson said. "We just didn't have the energy down the stretch." Reserve guard Lue scored 11 points and Josh Childress added eight in the third quarter as Atlanta scored a season-high 38 points in the period and cut a 25-point deficit to six. The Hawks pulled to 80-75 on two free throws by Marvin Williams with 10:35 remaining in the game but got no closer. "The past few games, we've been coming up big in the fourth quarter, and tonight we just didn't have it," Johnson said. "We fought back and exhausted ourselves trying to get back in the game," Hawks coach Mike Woodson added. "We've got to figure out how to play back-to-back (games). We've struggled with that all year." Jamison's 3-pointer gave Washington an 88-77 lead with 6:19 left. Arenas scored five points as the Wizards opened the third quarter with a 9-2 run. Butler's two free throws capped the spurt and gave Washington a 55-35 lead. Arenas gave Washington a 40-29 lead with a steal and breakaway dunk with 4:55 remaining in the second quarter. Brendan Haywood's follow shot with 2 seconds left gave the Wizards a 46-33 halftime lead. The Hawks' 33 points in the first half were a season low for Wizards' opponents. The Wizards ended the first quarter with a 16-3 run and led 24-15 after one. Jamison, who had 12 points and nine rebounds in the first half, scored five points and Butler added four in the Wizards' 11-0 run that gave them a 19-11 lead.

Game notes
Lue, a former Wizards player, ranks third in the league in 3-point shooting percentage at 46 percent. ... Veteran referee Dick Bavetta quipped to a courtside heckler: "Take it easy on me over there. I'm not leaving you any more tickets." ... Arenas is one of four players who rank in the league's top 20 in scoring and assists. LeBron James, Allen Iverson and Dwyane Wade are the other three.<
